SYMPTOM_TEXT: During first 15 minutes after dose began to feel sensation in jaw on the same side as injection (left). After left site, felt sensation from elbow into pinky and ring finger like a tingling. This persisted on and off throughout the following days up to and including today (4/6/21).  The sensation has been at times worse. The feeling in face/jaw has been like novocaine wearing off after having dental work. The sensation in arm has gone up to underarm  and down along leg into toes. This sensation could be described as feeling like these areas are "waking up after falling asleep"/a tingling sensation/mild numbness, though I have never lost ability move these areas and can still feel them. Pain in my hip and elbow has developed on that side (left) . So far, only very temporary similar sensation in right foot on outside of the foot. On 3/18/21 (8th day after injection) I developed a large (as big as my hand with fingers spread out) red, warm, hard  area at and around the injection site. I saw pictures of this on the internet and mine looked very typical to that. This lasted about 5 days. A couple of those days, my left breast felt bruised. On the 13th day after the injection, I had a fever, chills and slept most of the day. Fever and chills only lasted that one day.  My greatest concern is about the numbness/tingling because it has persisted and not subsided. Here I am a month after the first dose and I tire easily. I think the tiredness may be stemming from the persistent numbness/tingling sensations. I
LAB_DATA: I have not had any tests. I did go to see the Nurse Practitioner at my doctor's office to discuss these side effects and get advice on whether I should get second dose.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient was nervous upon receipt of vaccine.  It was an unscheduled (expiring) dose.  Per parent, he had fallen asleep outside vaccine room and they had to wake him up to get vaccine.   I gave immunization and asked him to stay for 15 minutes afterwards.  His Mom ran to consult window to notify staff patient was passing out.  I was sanitizing vaccine room so I immediately ran to him and his Dad and I caught him as he was slumping over.  He was shaking really hard, weak, and clammy.  He was coherent b/c I asked him his name but did not have clear recollection of timing of vaccine.  He was very pale in color.  His Mom grabbed him a Gatorade and he seemed very thirsty as he was drinking.  He mentioned he felt dizzy and that both arms were hurting and the arm I gave vaccine in felt like he had sweat dripping off it.  (I felt his arm and it did not).  I grabbed an instant cold pack and placed on his neck to help cool him off.  His color returned over the 30 minutes.  I asked parents if they wanted me to call ambulance but they wanted to wait and see how he responded.  He looked at his iPhone data and his heart rate had spiked.  Unclear if right before vaccine or right after but I believe he mentioned it went up to 120 when Mom said his normal resting heart rate was 60.  He ate some gold fish and seemed to perk up and have a few funny conversations showing his personality.  I explained to him very important to let parents know if he experienced any other side effects after leaving.  He was able to stand up and walk out of RX with parents.

Essential hypertension    MEDICAL DECISION MAKING 75-year-old female presents today to the emergency department for evaluation of symptoms after receiving her 1st COVID-19 shot.  Upon arrival to emergency depart patient is well-appearing and nontoxic.  Vital signs reviewed.  Patient is fairly hypertensive.  She describes the symptoms coming on immediately after shot.  Her neurologic examination is strong.  I do not appreciate any evidence of allergic reaction at this time.  Because of her hypertension here in the emergency department did assess basic labs.  She is given 0.1 mg of oral clonidine.  Blood pressure show significant improvement.  Patient is feeling much better at this time.  Certainly may have been a component of blood pressure here so I am unsure if this was related to her COVID-19 shot.  I did discussed follow-up with primary care physician as well as return criteria.  Patient is discharged in stable and improved condition. 15 days later, felt pressure in the ear, distorted sound and whooshing sounds.  No fluid in the ear.  No other conditions observed. GP suggested antihistamines and ibuprofen for a couple of days.  Third day after onset I called ENT who performed hearing test (see next box) and provided me with oral prednisone.  After 3 days of no improvement, she added local injections through the ear drum of cortisone (a series of 3 of these, one  every three days)
